{"parse":{"title":"Ben Aronson","pageid":33229771,"revid":859445848,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux\" style=\"display:none\">American painter</div>\n<table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">Ben Aronson\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Closed-Ramp-2010,-84x74-wikipedia.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Closed-Ramp-2010%2C-84x74-wikipedia.jpg/104px-Closed-Ramp-2010%2C-84x74-wikipedia.jpg\" width=\"104\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Closed-Ramp-2010%2C-84x74-wikipedia.jpg/156px-Closed-Ramp-2010%2C-84x74-wikipedia.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Closed-Ramp-2010%2C-84x74-wikipedia.jpg/208px-Closed-Ramp-2010%2C-84x74-wikipedia.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"247\" data-file-height=\"285\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><i>Closed Ramp</i>, 2010, oil on linen, 84 \u00d7 74 inches\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul></span></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span style=\"display:none\"> (<span class=\"bday\">1958-10-04</span>) </span>October 4, 1958<span class=\"noprint ForceAgeToShow\"> (age&#160;59)</span><br /><span class=\"birthplace\">Boston, Massachusetts</span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Nationality</th><td class=\"category\">\nAmerican</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Education</th><td>\nBoston University</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Known&#160;for</th><td>\nPainting, Printmaking</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Movement</th><td class=\"category\">\nAbstract Realism</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Awards</th><td>\nNational Academy of Design (2005), Childe Hassam Purchase Prize (American Academy of Arts and Letters (2006)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Website</th><td>\n<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.benaronson.net\">www.benaronson.net</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Ben Aronson</b> (born October 4, 1958) is an American painter living in Massachusetts.  His work is represented by Tibor de Nagy Gallery<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> in New York, Jenkins Johnson Gallery<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> in San Francisco, and Alpha Gallery<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> in Boston.\n</p><p>One of the strongest urban scene painters working today,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Groff_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Groff-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>  Aronson's painterly urban landscapes combine precise realism with gestural immediacy and <a href=\"/wiki/Abstract_Expressionist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Abstract Expressionist\">Abstract Expressionist</a> energy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kuspit_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kuspit-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  His work has become influential among, and emulated by many contemporary cityscape painters.  His paintings are included in the permanent collections of more than fifty museums throughout the U.S. and abroad, including the <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Fine_Arts,_Boston\" title=\"Museum of Fine Arts, Boston\">Museum of Fine Arts, Boston</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-MFA_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MFA-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> the <a href=\"/wiki/Virginia_Museum_of_Fine_Arts\" title=\"Virginia Museum of Fine Arts\">Virginia Museum of Fine Arts</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/De_Young_Museum\" title=\"De Young Museum\">De Young Museum</a> in San Francisco, The <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Fine_Arts,_Houston\" title=\"Museum of Fine Arts, Houston\">Museum of Fine Arts, Houston</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Eli_and_Edythe_Broad_Art_Museum\" title=\"Eli and Edythe Broad Art Museum\">Eli and Edythe Broad Art Museum</a>, MI, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Suzhou_Museum\" title=\"Suzhou Museum\">Suzhou Museum</a>, Jiangsu Province, China, as well as numerous private and institutional collections.<sup id=\"cite_ref-artnet_biography_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-artnet_biography-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>\"Aronson's luscious impastos depict Manhattan's skyscrapers and concrete canyons, Paris's stately buildings, and San Francisco's skyline with great dexterity\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-Miller_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Miller-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> winning acclaim as \"...the real deal: the rich physicality of oil paint married to the mutable physics of perception\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Baker_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Baker-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In recent years his cityscapes have evolved to include contemporary social realist themes \"...in which Aronson moves the human figure from its lesser role within the larger urban landscape, into a full subject of its own.  Echoing his dramatically lighted single object still lifes, the solitary figures have now taken their place on stage with equal poignancy.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-O&#39;Hern_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-O&#39;Hern-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> (Images/Nighthawks Series)<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>  Exhibits at the <a href=\"/wiki/Tibor_de_Nagy_Gallery\" title=\"Tibor de Nagy Gallery\">Tibor de Nagy Gallery</a>, NYC (\"Risk and Reward\", 2010) and the <a href=\"/wiki/Ogunquit_Museum_of_American_Art\" title=\"Ogunquit Museum of American Art\">Ogunquit Museum of American Art</a>, Maine (\"Aronson to Aronson\", 2011) revealed a new emphasis on social realism in a series of paintings with Wall Street themes exploring the contemporary world of big business.  His \"... scenes of the <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_Stock_Exchange\" title=\"New York Stock Exchange\">New York Stock Exchange</a> floor in particular reveal one of the most energized and sophisticated brushes in the country.  His high-contrast tones, boldly thick paint and slashing marks perfectly mirror the fast-moving, high-powered and high-tech world.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kany_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kany-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Donald_Kuspit\" title=\"Donald Kuspit\">Donald Kuspit</a>, professor of art history and philosophy (SUNY Stony Brook, Cornell) observes: \"whatever social narrative is conveyed by Aronson's pictures, they are all exquisitely painted and emotionally haunting.  Aronson is a social realist, like <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Hopper\" title=\"Edward Hopper\">Edward Hopper</a>\u2014but he's dealing with a different [our current] social reality\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kuspit_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kuspit-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Biography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Biography</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Images\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Images</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Biography\">Biography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ben_Aronson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Biography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Ben Aronson was born in Boston and grew up in Sudbury, Massachusetts.\n</p><p>From early childhood he was immersed in the creative environment of his parents and their friends among professional artists, art dealers, writers, musicians, composers, and actors.  He interned at a Boston architectural firm while in high school and considered pursuing architecture at Princeton and Yale. Ultimately deciding on fine art as his path of choice, he enrolled at the School of Fine Arts at Boston University where he earned his BFA and MFA in painting (1976\u20131982) studying under <a href=\"/wiki/Philip_Guston\" title=\"Philip Guston\">Philip Guston</a>, James Weeks, <a href=\"/wiki/David_Aronson\" title=\"David Aronson\">David Aronson</a>, Reed Kay, and John Wilson.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Grant_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Grant-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Traveled to Europe in 1978 to study collections in Greece, Paris, the Netherlands, Spain, and Italy. Taught fine art at <a href=\"/wiki/Beaver_Country_Day_School\" title=\"Beaver Country Day School\">Beaver Country Day School</a>, a private high school in Chestnut Hill, MA from1983 to 1990. In 1990, he left teaching for work as an architectural illustrator which won him a prestigious international award from the American Society of Architectural Perspectivists in 1991.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ASAP_14-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ASAP-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>  From 1995 to 2007 he was invited yearly to lecture and teach in a Drawing Seminar for architecture students at the <a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_Graduate_School_of_Design\" title=\"Harvard Graduate School of Design\">Harvard Graduate School of Design</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Grant_13-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Grant-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the years since 1990 his work began to appear frequently in group and solo exhibitions at galleries in California, New York City, Chicago and New England.  He has presented over 20 solo exhibitions at respected galleries across the U.S., including <a href=\"/wiki/Tibor_de_Nagy_Gallery\" title=\"Tibor de Nagy Gallery\">Tibor de Nagy Gallery</a>, New York (2005, 2008, 2010), Jenkins Johnson Gallery, San Francisco (2004, 2007, 2008, 2011), Alpha Gallery, Boston (2000, 2002, 2006, 2009).  He was elected into the <a href=\"/wiki/National_Academy_of_Design\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"National Academy of Design\">National Academy of Design</a> <sup id=\"cite_ref-NAD_15-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NAD-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> in New York City in 2004.\n</p><p>Aronson shares a family tradition in the arts.  His father, <a href=\"/wiki/David_Aronson\" title=\"David Aronson\">David Aronson</a>, is one of a major group of Boston painters known as the <a href=\"/wiki/Boston_Expressionism\" title=\"Boston Expressionism\">Boston Expressionists</a> which includes <a href=\"/wiki/Jack_Levine\" title=\"Jack Levine\">Jack Levine</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hyman_Bloom\" title=\"Hyman Bloom\">Hyman Bloom</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Karl_Zerbe\" title=\"Karl Zerbe\">Karl Zerbe</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Grant_13-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Grant-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>  David Aronson also founded the visual arts department at Boston University in 1955.  His paintings and sculptures are represented in numerous major museum collections.  His mother, Georgianna Nyman Aronson, is a respected American portrait painter who has produced official portraits of seven of the Justices of the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Supreme_Court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States Supreme Court\">United States Supreme Court</a>.\n</p><p>Ben Aronson\u2019s two sons, Jesse (b. 1984) and Alex (b. 1987) are both pursuing successful careers in the visual arts.\n</p><p>He lives with his wife, Eileen, at their home and studio in Massachusetts.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Images\">Images</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ben_Aronson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Images\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><b>\u201cClosed Ramp\u201d</b>\n</p><p>Aronson's cityscapes won acclaim as \u201c...the real deal: the rich physicality of oil paint married to the mutable physics of perception.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-Village_Voice_16-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Village_Voice-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-17\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><b>\"The Recollection\"</b>\n</p><p>\"Aronson's luscious impastos depict Manhattan skyscrapers and concrete canyons, Paris's stately buildings, and San Francisco's skyline with great dexterity.  In these cityscapes, he contrasts blurry, impressionistic foregrounds with near-photorealistic distant views.  The artist's figurative works are equally deft.  In <i>The Recollection</i> (2008), the precise detailing of the fine restaurant in the background opposes the gauziness of the young blond woman whose blue eyes seem lost in reverie.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Miller_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Miller-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-18\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ben_Aronson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.tibordenagy.com/artists/ben-aronson\">Tibor de Nagy Gallery</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.jenkinsjohnsongallery.com/artists/aronson/aronson_main.html\">Jenkins Johnson Gallery</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20120424230426/http://www.jenkinsjohnsongallery.com/artists/aronson/aronson_main.html\">Archived</a> April 24, 2012, at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.alphagallery.com/artists/aronson.html\">Alpha Gallery</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20111209065406/http://www.alphagallery.com/artists/aronson.html\">Archived</a> December 9, 2011, at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Groff-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Groff_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Groff, Larry (March 2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.paintingperceptions.com/comtemporary-realism/ben-aronson\">\"Ben Aronson\"</a>. Painting Perceptions.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Ben+Aronson&amp;rft.pub=Painting+Perceptions&amp;rft.date=2009-03&amp;rft.aulast=Groff&amp;rft.aufirst=Larry&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.paintingperceptions.com%2Fcomtemporary-realism%2Fben-aronson&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABen+Aronson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Kuspit-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kuspit_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kuspit_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Kuspit, Donald (October 2010). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/kuspit/ben-aronson11-24-10.asp\">\"Mood of Money\"</a>. Artnet.com.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Mood+of+Money&amp;rft.pub=Artnet.com&amp;rft.date=2010-10&amp;rft.aulast=Kuspit&amp;rft.aufirst=Donald&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.artnet.com%2Fmagazineus%2Ffeatures%2Fkuspit%2Fben-aronson11-24-10.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABen+Aronson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-MFA-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-MFA_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Museum of Fine Arts, Boston (2005). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.mfa.org/collections/object/over-madison-48159\">\"Over Madison\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Over+Madison&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.aulast=M